summary:
Hungarians cast ballots Sunday in a parliamentary election where opposition leader Péter Magyar challenges Prime Minister Viktor Orbán's 16-year rule. Polls show a tight race between Orbán's Fidesz party and the Tisza alliance led by Magyar. The election determines Hungary's next government. Voter turnout exceeded 50% by midday. Results expected Monday. This follows EU sanctions on Hungary over rule-of-law issues.

US and Iran delegations held direct talks in Islamabad, Pakistan, Sunday to end a six-week war disrupting Middle East shipping and energy supplies. The meeting marks the first direct negotiations since 1979. The US cleared mines from the Strait of Hormuz prior to talks. No agreement announced. Pakistan hosts mediation. Success would stabilize oil prices affecting global markets. Separately in the Middle East, Israel permitted thousands of displaced Palestinians to cross a bisecting military zone back to northern Gaza after a hostage release agreement broke a prior deadlock. The move affects humanitarian access in the enclave.

Rwanda-backed M23 rebels overran Congolese troops and entered Goma Sunday, displacing over 1 million residents in the eastern Congo aid hub amid gunfire and shelling. United Nations monitors report threats to humanitarian operations. NATO launched a coordinated response after sabotage severed a Baltic Sea power cable between Lithuania and Sweden, following a prior undersea cable cut affecting Finland and Germany. NASA's Artemis II crew—Reid Wiseman, Christina Koch, Jeremy Hansen, and Victor Glover—landed safely in the Pacific off California after orbiting the moon. In New York, NYPD officers shot dead a man who stabbed three people at 42nd Street-Grand Central subway station; victims received hospital treatment. Nigeria convicted 386 Islamist terror suspects in a mass trial tied to Boko Haram insurgency."}
